<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB553442040F2E65C4DB93E" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="436" pageId="4" pageNumber="435" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB553452040F2E65684B6FB" blockId="4.[1405,2612,3393,3474]" pageId="4" pageNumber="435">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB553452040F2E65927B613" bold="true" box="[1406,1561,3393,3426]" pageId="4" pageNumber="435">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB553452319F2E65881B613" authority="Meyen, 1833" authorityName="Meyen" authorityYear="1833" box="[1575,1983,3393,3426]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="4" pageNumber="435" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="musteloides">Galea musteloides Meyen, 1833</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="3B3E3C8CFFB5534522F1F2E65688B6FB" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3784487320" pageId="4" pageNumber="435">“auf dem Passe von Tacna nach dem Alpensee von Titicaca [= on the pass of Tacna to the alpine lake of Titicaca],” Peru</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442621FEBD5C4DB93E" blockId="5.[792,1390,282,710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
Much published data on 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB4534421ADFEBD5A71BA4A" authorityName="Meyen" authorityYear="1833" box="[1171,1359,282,315]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="musteloides">G. musteloides</taxonomicName>
is actually from G. leucoblephara based on a revision of 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB4534426F0FECE5B26BAFB" authorityName="Meyen" authorityYear="1832" box="[974,1048,361,394]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Galea</taxonomicName>
by J. L. Dunnum and J. Salazar-Bravo in 2010. The “Muenster Yellow-toothed Cavy,” C. monasteriensis, is considered here a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB4534421CEFE475C59B959" authorityName="Meyen" authorityYear="1833" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="musteloides">G. musteloides</taxonomicName>
boliviensis. Three subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB453442620FDF25CF3B813" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="synonymic_list">
<caption id="DF296659FFB453442620FDF25CF3B813" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6585544" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6585544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6585544/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" targetBox="[183,774,289,704]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442620FDF25B81B907" blockId="5.[792,1390,282,710]" box="[798,1215,597,630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB453442620FDF25B81B907" bold="true" box="[798,1215,597,630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Subspecies and Distribution.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB45344261FFD215E35B99A" blockId="5.[792,1390,282,710]" lastBlockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB45344261FFD215BEEB9EE" authority="Meyen, 1833" authorityName="Meyen" authorityYear="1833" box="[801,1232,646,671]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="musteloides" subSpecies="musteloides">G.m.musteloidesMeyen,1833—AndeanAltiplano,inSEPeru,WBolivia,andNChile.</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442584FD5C5C6EB84A" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB453442584FD5C5D15B865" authority="Thomas, 1911" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1911" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[186,555,763,788]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="musteloides" subSpecies="auceps">G.m.aucepsThomas,1911—highlandareasSofLakeTiticacainSEPeru(PunoDepartment)andWBolivia(LaPazDepartment).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442584FCE65CF3B813" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" box="[186,973,833,866]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB453442584FCE65DB4B813" authority="Waterhouse, 1848" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1848" box="[186,650,833,866]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Galea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="musteloides" subSpecies="boliviensis">G. m. boliviensis Waterhouse, 1848</taxonomicName>
— E Bolivian Altiplano.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB453442589FCD65B42BF56" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442589FCD65B42BF56" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB453442589FCD65E91B8FB" bold="true" box="[183,431,881,906]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
There are no specific data available, but external measurements are likely similar to the Lowland Yellow-toothed Cavy (G. leucoblephara). Highland Yellowtoothed Cavies are characterized by brownish fur, with yellowish to olive dorsal tinge. Venteris white; dorsal and ventral colors are distinctly demarcated. Ears have covers of yellowish brown hairs—a characteristic that varies among subspecies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB453442588FB895EBBBFEC" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442588FB895EBBBFEC" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB453442588FB895E1BBF3E" bold="true" box="[182,293,1070,1103]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Habitat.</emphasis>
High-elevation grasslands in the central Andes. Highland Yellow-Toothed Cavies either build burrows or occupy abandoned burrows of tuco-tucos (
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB4534421D7FBF15A5ABF06" authorityName="Blainville" authorityYear="1826" box="[1257,1380,1110,1143]" class="Mammalia" family="Ctenomyidae" genus="Ctenomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ctenomys</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB453442589FB275E46BFEC" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1842" box="[183,376,1152,1181]" class="Mammalia" family="Ctenomyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Ctenomyidae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB453442588FB035B44BFB4" box="[182,1146,1188,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442588FB035B44BFB4" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" box="[182,1146,1188,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB453442588FB035E85BFB4" bold="true" box="[182,443,1188,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
There is no information available forthis species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB453442588FB6B5E43BE62" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB453442588FB6B5E43BE62" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB453442588FB6B5E02BF9C" bold="true" box="[182,316,1228,1261]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Breeding.</emphasis>
Gestation is ¢.55 days (50-58). Litter sizes are 1-7 young; neonates weigh c.40 g at birth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB45344258AFABC5A61BE4D" box="[180,1375,1307,1340]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="activity">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB45344258AFABC5A61BE4D" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" box="[180,1375,1307,1340]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB45344258AFABC5EA1BE4D" bold="true" box="[180,415,1307,1340]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Highland Yellow-toothed Cavy is diurnal and active year-round.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB45344258BFAE55CBFBDEC" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB45344258BFAE55CBFBDEC" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB45344258BFAE55C50BE12" bold="true" box="[181,878,1346,1379]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Much ofthe literature on the Highland Yellow-Toothed Cavy reports it to be promiscuous, but these studies were actually conducted on the Lowland Yellow-toothed Cavy. Social behavior of the Highland Yellow-toothed Cavy was studied as the “Muenster Yellow-toothed Cavy,” now a synonym of the subspecies boliviensis. Studies on a captive colony of the Highland Yellow-toothed Cavy suggest that it is monogamous. Unfamiliar individuals are extremely aggressive toward each other, but established pairs showed no aggression, even when separated and reunited. This is a relatively rare example of monogamy in mammals, as also occurs in the Patagonian 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB4534424C5F9DB5D7DBDEC" box="[507,579,1660,1693]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Mara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Mara</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C564D52FFB453442769F9DB5C4ABDEC" baseAuthorityName="Zimmermann" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[599,884,1660,1693]" class="Mammalia" family="Caviidae" genus="Dolichotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="patagonum">Dolichotis patagonum</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34C655AFFB45344258BF90F5C9ABC13" pageId="5" pageNumber="436" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BE936D1FFB45344258BF90F5C9ABC13" blockId="5.[180,1389,714,1970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis id="B922EAC3FFB45344258BF90F5D2CBDB4" bold="true" box="[181,530,1704,1733]" pageId="5" pageNumber="436">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List (as G. monasteriensis, now one of three subspecies, boliviensis, of the Highland Yellow-Toothed Cavy). The current IUCN assessment applies more correctly to the broadly distributed Lowland Yellow-toothed Cavy (G. leucoblephara). The overall conservation status of the Highland Yellow-toothed Cavy needs to be reassessed.
</paragraph>
